Code Structure\
--------------\
1. **Data Preparation**\
   - Loads and cleans GPS individual-level data.\
   - Merges with country-level macroeconomic crisis data.\
   - Harmonises variable names and constructs relevant covariates.\
\
2. **Treatment Variable Construction**\
   - Identifies crisis episodes following Barro and Urs\'faa (2008): cumulative and consecutive declines of at least 10%\
     in real GDP per capita between the peak and the first year of positive growth.\
   - Assigns exposure during impressionable years (ages 18\'9625) to determine whether an individual was affected by a crisis.\
   - Constructs both binary and continuous exposure indicators.\
\
3. **Model Estimation**\
   - Runs baseline OLS and high-dimensional fixed effects models (using `reghdfe`).\
   - Controls include sex, cognitive ability, democracy, and government redistribution levels.\
   - Standard errors are clustered at the cohort-country level.\
\
4. **Robustness and Sensitivity Analyses**\
   - Tests robustness to alternative crisis-severity thresholds (\uc0\u8805 9% to \u8805 3% GDP decline).\
   - Performs sensitivity analyses.\
   - Conducts heterogeneity analysis based on redistribution environments.\
\
5. **Output Generation**\
   - Exports regression tables, descriptive summaries, and coefficient plots for publication figures.\
\
Required Stata Packages\
-----------------------\
- reghdfe (for fixed-effects estimation)\
- estout (for storing regression results)\
- coefplot (for coefficient plots)\
- outreg2 (for regression output formatting)\
-psacalc (to execute the Oster (2019) test)\
- ftools (dependency for reghdfe)\
\
Reproducibility Notes\
---------------------\
- All datasets must be stored in the same working directory before execution.\
- File paths should be updated in the \'93global directory\'94 section of the do-file.\
- Run the code sequentially to ensure full replication of results.\
